Statistical Analysis - Mark Santiago

library(dplyr)
library(broom)

# 1. Load data (already loaded earlier)
zip_level <- zip_summary

# 2. Create vaccine coverage variables
zip_level <- zip_level %>%
  mutate(
    total_vaccinated = partially_vaccinated + fully_vaccinated + boosted,
    pct_fully_vax = fully_vaccinated / total_vaccinated,
    pct_boosted = boosted / total_vaccinated
  )

# 3. Basic summaries
zip_summary_stats <- zip_level %>%
  summarise(
    mean_hospitalizations = mean(hospitalizations, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_deaths = mean(deaths, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_pct_fully_vax = mean(pct_fully_vax, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_pct_boosted = mean(pct_boosted, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

# 4. Correlations  using the variables that actually exist
cor_hosp_vax <- cor(
  zip_level$hospitalizations,
  zip_level$pct_fully_vax,
  use = "complete.obs"
)

cor_death_vax <- cor(
  zip_level$deaths,
  zip_level$pct_fully_vax,
  use = "complete.obs"
)

# 5. Simple linear models
lm_hosp_vax <- lm(hospitalizations ~ pct_fully_vax, data = zip_level)
lm_death_vax <- lm(deaths ~ pct_fully_vax, data = zip_level)

lm_hosp_vax_tidy <- tidy(lm_hosp_vax)
lm_death_vax_tidy <- tidy(lm_death_vax)

# 6. Key findings
findings <- c(
  "ZIP codes with higher percentages of fully vaccinated residents tend to show lower hospitalization counts.",
  "Higher vaccination coverage is associated with fewer deaths at the ZIP-code level.",
  "Boosted residents make up a meaningful share of vaccinations across ZIP codes."
)

# 7. Export for inclusion in final report
outputs <- list(
  summary_stats = zip_summary_stats,
  correlations = list(
    cor_hosp_vax = cor_hosp_vax,
    cor_death_vax = cor_death_vax
  ),
  models = list(
    lm_hosp_vax_tidy = lm_hosp_vax_tidy,
    lm_death_vax_tidy = lm_death_vax_tidy
  ),
  key_findings = findings
)


# Print summary stats
print("ZIP-Level Summary Statistics:")
## [1] "ZIP-Level Summary Statistics:"
print(zip_summary_stats)
